      "question": "If $\\sec \\theta + \\tan \\theta = p$, prove that $\\sin \\theta = \\frac{p^2 - 1}{p^2 + 1}$.",
      "answer": "$\\sin \\theta = \\frac{p^2 - 1}{p^2 + 1}$",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "Use the identity $\\sec^2 \\theta - \\tan^2 \\theta = 1$ to find $\\sec \\theta - \\tan \\theta$.",
          "Since $(\\sec \\theta + \\tan \\theta)(\\sec \\theta - \\tan \\theta) = 1$, then $\\sec \\theta - \\tan \\theta = 1/p$.",
          "Solve the system of two linear equations to find $\\sec \\theta$ and $\\tan \\theta$ in terms of $p$.",
          "Calculate $p^2 - 1$ and $p^2 + 1$ using the expressions found.",
          "Divide $(p^2 - 1)$ by $(p^2 + 1)$ and simplify to show it equals $\\sin \\theta$."
        ],
        "derivation": "Given $p = \\sec \\theta + \\tan \\theta$. We know $\\sec^2 \\theta - \\tan^2 \\theta = 1 \\implies (\\sec \\theta - \\tan \\theta) = \\frac{1}{p}$. Adding equations: $2\\sec \\theta = p + \\frac{1}{p} = \\frac{p^2+1}{p} \\implies \\cos \\theta = \\frac{2p}{p^2+1}$. Subtracting equations: $2\\tan \\theta = p - \\frac{1}{p} = \\frac{p^2-1}{p} \\implies \\tan \\theta = \\frac{p^2-1}{2p}$. Since $\\sin \\theta = \\tan \\theta \\cdot \\cos \\theta = \\frac{p^2-1}{2p} \\cdot \\frac{2p}{p^2+1} = \\frac{p^2-1}{p^2+1}$."
      },
